               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400511-name-399" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400511-name-399" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400511-name-399" type="surname" value="WILLIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400511-name-399" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL WILLIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am foreman at Ralph Wilcoxon's shoe-warehouse, in Tottenham Court-road. On the 27th of April, between one and half-past one o'clock, Barrett came into our shop, and gave information—I ran out, and overtook the prisoner at some distance—I charged him with having something that did not belong to him—he drew these boots from under his coat, and gave them to me—they are my master's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400511-name-400" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400511-name-400" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400511-name-400" type="surname" value="BARRETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400511-name-400" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BARRETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I saw the prisoner coming from towards the shop, and going up Howland-street with the boots and the ticket on them—I gave information, and the witness brought him back—he begged very hard of Mr. Wilcoxon to forgive him, or place him where he might be taken care of.</p>
